Before diving in, I’m curious to see the distribution of my data as well as the distribution of the older, messier data. Everyone likes an ego boost. After running the summary, since most of my variables are dummies, nothing is too surprising. I then compare it to the data as it was. As I suspeced, the qualitative data is not ideal for summary statistics or analysis. However, despite my cleaning, the summary is not incredibly helpful. I then make a quick set of barcharts to view the distribution of the data. One could also facet wrap and use ggplot functionality; however, since the graphs are only for personal eye-balling, base R graphics do the job.

corr <- cor(census_train)

This gives me a playground to do more work with variable selection. Given the time, this would be one technique I’d use as a gut check for feature selection when building a model.

# runApp()

First, I run a simple logistic regression using all the variables in my arsenal. The output shows me that, given my model, only 347 respondents make over 50k and the rest under 50k. Because I have labeled data, I know the rate to be much higher. As it stands, the proportion of those making over 50k is about 6%, whereas my model predicts about 2%. There is some work to be done. For this model, because I believe it to be biased, I don’t waste time constructing a ROC curve to test it’s predictive power.

lm <- glm(data = census_train,formula =  over50k ~ ., family=binomial(link= "logit"))

Using a stepwise model, I find the ideal formula given the variables that I have, which selects only the variables of importance. Since there are still many variables, I suspect overfitting. I would also explore the “Leave One Out” step to find the optimal point at which my model had enough predictive power before introducing variable covariance.

For better or for worse, I’ve decided to stick with lm2. At this point, I’m curious about it’s real predictive power. So, at this point, I apply the model to my test data. I extract the classification error from my model to back out its accuracy. I’m pleasantly surprised that the model has 94.7% accuracy.

predResults <- predict(lm2, newdata=census_test,type='response')
predResults <- ifelse(predResults > 0.5,1,0)

classificationError <- mean(predResults != census_test$over50k, na.rm = T)
print(paste('Accuracy',1-classificationError))
## [1] "Accuracy 0.947086498706695"

Lastly, out of curiosity, I construct a decision tree; I used the same variables that had shown a significant relationship on the dependent variable. I found that the tree actually out performed my logistic regression in terms of lift. The tree did relatively well when pitted against the test data and predicted accurately for a majority of the classifications.

tree <- rpart(over50k ~ ageSq + male + normalizedWageHr + foreignDad + 
    wksWorkedPastYr + black + unemployed + belowCollege + college + 
    aboveMasters + married + householder + bothParents + blackDivorcedM + 
    hispanicDivorcedM, data = census_train, method = "class")

Analysis and final write up

Ultimately, I chose the SVM model. The error is significantly lower than the error that I found in my second logistic model. And while the tree did not perform terribly, the high dimensionality in the data may not suit the model well.

Given the output, I found that:

  • Those who identified black are likelier to make less than 50k
  • Those who were not householders were less likely to make 50k
  • Those who had higher education were likelier to make over 50k
  • Households were both parents were present were likelier to make over 50k
  • One surprising finding: Hispanic divorced males were likelier ot make less than 50k

While the models pointed to interesting outcomes, none of it came as a shock. All of the typical variables associated with being a minority were found here to be a drain on annual income. If anything, the results were reiffying. More poignantly would be to gather current Census data to see if the model would still work on current data. I believe the differential, or the misclassification rate, would point ot areas where income disparities have improved and for which demographics.

The data highlight a story of single parents, often of color, who are struggling to make a living wage to support themselves, or themselves and a family. Yet, I believe that this limited inspection does not do justice to the multi-faceted narrative. I believe build a comprehensive model to extrapolate meaningful analysis, one would have to pull in many other data sets to get at the root of causal influence on income and reduce omitted variable biases.

Yet, it is worth noting that the data was not normally distributed. Most of the data recorded was by respondents who in fact earned less than 50k, which points to the fact that this may not be a representative sample. So, while we can say these factors are strong predicitors amongst those in this sample, we cannot apply it to the population. Moving forward, I would want to weight the data given the normal demographic spread we’d see in the world.

Challenges

Most of my challenges were time based. Typically, I would spend much longer structuring the data differently for different models. Accordingly, I was not being as keen to watch out for bias in my models, which was certainly present. However, the typical bias-variance tradeoff reared its ugly head, and I decided to err more towards capturing explanatory power versus it being strictly accurate in this case; that was something out of character and honestly difficult to get past. I also experienced challenges up front when cleaning the data. Because the data was messy and primarily quantitative, I weighed considerations between factorizing the data or making a series of dummy variables.

I would have also liked to create more interaction variables. I know that the variables to not meet the assumption of independence and thusly muddy up the findings. In hindsight, and given more time, I would have constructed the model very differently. However, as an explatory first pass I was interested in the findings.
